The paper deals with privacy properties of the Sampled Gaussian Mechanism (SGM), which is a commonly used technique in machine learning applications. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the categories of computer security (cs.CR) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the Renyi Differential Privacy, which is a relaxation of the notion of differential privacy, indicating that it may belong to the categories of information theory (cs.IT) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper's focus on privacy amplification by sampling suggests that it may also belong to the category of social and information networks (cs.SI).
